TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Polynomially Bounded Algorithm for a Nonlinear Network Allocation Problem
AU  - Elken, T. R.
AU  - Freedman, H. T.
AU  - Gibson, A. E.
Y1  - 1981/09/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.27.9.1054
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.27.9.1054
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1054
EP  - 1066
VL  - 27
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper presents an algorithm for determining the optimal allocation to demand points when the distribution system is a capacitated arborescence of N arcs and the cost (return) functions are convex (concave). It is proved that the algorithm generates an optimal solution by solving at most N(N + 1)/2 single-constraint subproblems. If the cost functions allow the Lagrange multiplier for the subproblems to be evaluated in polynomial time, then this is a polynomial algorithm. The analysis is motivated by the problem of allocating spare capacity in the loop plant portion of telephone networks.
AB  - This paper presents an algorithm for determining the optimal allocation to demand points when the distribution system is a capacitated arborescence of N arcs and the cost (return) functions are convex (concave). It is proved that the algorithm generates an optimal solution by solving at most N(N + 1)/2 single-constraint subproblems. If the cost functions allow the Lagrange multiplier for the subproblems to be evaluated in polynomial time, then this is a polynomial algorithm. The analysis is motivated by the problem of allocating spare capacity in the loop plant portion of telephone networks.
